title: For Sale:  Smith and Wesson 442 Pro J Frame Revolver
postcontent:
This Smith and Wesson model 442 Pro (No Lock model) is about 1 month old and is like new.  Comes with the original Smith & Wesson case, lock, documentation and 3 brand new moon clips.

S&W introduced a new Model 442 as part of its “Pro” series. The Pro line is positioned between the basic models and the high-end Performance Center models, as a cost-effective upgrade to the most critical “professional” features.
The 442 for the Pro series was named the Model 442 Moon Clip to emphasize its most unique feature. The newest 442 is equipped with a cylinder designed to use moon clips for increased speed and efficiency in loading. The use of moon clips requires additional machining on the face of the cylinder to accommodate the width of the metal clips. While this is an attractive feature for those shooters who prefer moon clips, the modifications do not affect the ability to load the revolver in more traditional ways—like using dump pouches, speed strips, or speedloaders.
Interestingly, the 442 Moon Clip also features a stainless steel cylinder rather than carbon steel. Since the entire gun is finished in matte black, that change is not readily apparent. Also of interest is the lack of an internal lock on the 442 Moon Clip.

Stop paying these idiots to ruin your guns.

The WASR10 is based on the PM-63, which is itself Romania's licensed copy of the Soviet AKM. 
The WASR10 has one of the best barrels in the AK world: made to spec., cold hammer forged, chromelined, and with 14mm threads at the muzzle.
It is arguably the single best part of the WASR, and known to give the same accuracy as the Saiga or SLR's barrel.

title: For Sale/Trade:   OBO Yugo Mauser 24/47 all matching with Royal Yugo and German markings
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Yugoslavian Mauser Model 24/47. This rifle is all matching numbers to include the receiver, barrel, stock, bolt and magazine (magazine is a forced match, the others are not).

This is not a Mitchell Mauser. It is import stamped.

Previous arsenal and manufacture markings were scrubbed on this one, but are still visible.
Faintly below the 24/47 markings Royal Yugo markings can be seen, as well as the location of original manufacture (Artillery Technical Institute). This makes original manufacture prewar (1928-31). Hard to get a picture of this as it is so faint, but it is there and I certainly welcome anyone to inspect it in person if they wish.

There are also two scrubbed German acceptance stamps, one on the receiver, indicating that the action (not the rifle as it sits today) was seized and put into German service, and one on the bolt release. So the action certainly saw combat during WWII.

The rifling is nearly flawless. The rifle does have some surface rust on the receiver, but this is limited and there is no corrosion. Not pretty but this rifle has been through a lot looking at the number/type of arsenal marks and stock markings.

Cycles great, shoots/groups dead on (though I don't have anywhere to shoot long range, so a little high at 100 yards as expected).

I have taken pictures of the rifle in and out, including all the markings should anyone wish to see more, ask questions etc.

All and all would make an all matching good shooter with a little bit of history behind it.

(Source for manufacture date/location)
http://candrsenal.com/rifle-serbian-mauser-model-1924/

title: For Sale:  380 rounds total of 308 - Freedom Munitions 175g Match Ammo and 147g Reman - 308.
postcontent:
I am selling 200 rounds of NEW Freedom 175g HPBT Match Ammo and 160 rounds of REMAN 147g FMJ 308 ammo. (all in the box, straight from Freedom)

 I have compared this ammo to LC XM118, FGMM, and Black Hills 175s......and I will take this every time over any of the previously mentioned ammo.

 If I didn't have time to hand load my own ammo, and I need ammo for a match, this is what I would use. When working up a new load, I load the rounds, then have my wife number the groups. That way, I do not know what load is what until after I have fired. One group that is always thrown in is a set of Freedoms.

 The picture is of my last set of Freedom's at the range. The flier was me, not the ammo. I was using a bipod and bag instead of my normal bench rest, and from my 20" Savage 10 FCP @ 100 yards (normally I shoot from my Custom FN SPR 24"). Still not too bad....but should have been better.
